nciation examples for Zinacant\u00e1n]\n*[http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Appendix:Swadesh_lists_for_Mayan_languages Comparative Tzotzil Swadesh vocabulary list] (from Wiktionary)\n*[http://www.ailla.utexas.org/search/collection.html?c_id=81 Mayan Languages Collection]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }} of [[Victoria Bricker]] at the [[Archive of the Indigenous Languages of Latin America]]. Contains recordings of Tzotzil made between 1964 and 1972. The recordings include those made of \"(1) elicited humorous narratives, songs, and prayers; (2) 'live' recordings of ritual humor at the fiestas of Saint Lawrence, Christmas, New Year's Day, Epiphany, and Saint Sebastian; and (3) didactic materials (lessons, texts, and exercises).\"\n*[https://www.bible.com/bible/757/MAT.1 SAN MATEO 1, Ach\u02bc Testamento: Ja\u02bc sc\u02bcoplal ti ja\u02bc Cajcoltavanejtic li Cajvaltic Jesucristoe (TZONT)] The [[New Testament]] in Tzotzil\n* D\u00edaz L\u00f3pez, \u00d3scar; et al. (2011). [https://site.inali.gob.mx/pdf/norma_tsotsil.pdf Smelolal sts\u02bcibael bats\u02bci k\u02bcop tsotsil / Norma de escritura de la lengua tsotsil] (First ed.). M\u00e9xico, D.F.: Instituto Nacional de Lenguas Ind\u00edgenas (INALI). {{ISBN|978-607-7538-44-8}}.\n\n\n\n{{Languages of Mexico}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tzotzil Language}}\n[[Category:Agglutinative languages]]\n[[Category:Mayan languages]]\n[[Category:Mesoamerican languages]]\n[[Category:Indigenous languages of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Verb\u2013object\u2013subject languages]]\n", "name_user": "Arjuno3", "label": "safe", "comment": "disamb.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tzotzil_language"}
{"title_page": "Oliver Building (Chicago)", "text_new": "{{About|the landmark Chicago building|the Pittsburgh skyscraper|Oliver Building (Pittsburgh)}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n | name =Oliver Building\n | nrhp_type =\n | image =Oliver Typewriter Building Front Door and Design.JPG \n | caption = Oliver Building Front Door with [[Oliver Typewriter Company]] ornamentation\n | designated_other1_name= Chicago Landmark\n | designated_other1_date= May 9, 1984\n | designated_other1_abbr= CL\n | designated_other1_link= Chicago Landmark\n | designated_other1_color= #aaccff\n | location= 159 N. Dearborn, [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States\n | coordinates = {{coord|41|53|05|N|87|37|45.5|W|display=inline,title}}\n| area =\n | built=1907-1908\n | architecture= \n | added = 1984\n | governing_body = Private\n | refnum=83003563 <ref name=\"nris\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/IL/Cook/state7.html|title=ILLINOIS - Cook County |date=2007-07-06|work=National Register of Historic Places|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref>\n}}\n[[File:Oliver Typewriter Company Logo on Building.JPG|thumb|left|upright|[[Oliver Typewriter Company]] ornamentation on Oliver Building (Chicago)]]\n\nThe '''Oliver Building''' is located at 159 N. Dearborn Street in [[Chicago]] within the [[Chicago Loop|Loop]]. It was built for the [[Oliver Typewriter Company]] from 1907-1908 by [[Holabird & Roche]]. When two floors were added in 1920, Holabird & Roche were hired for the expansion. The cast iron exterior features [[typewriter]]-related motifs. It was declared a [[Chicago Landmark]] on May 9, 1984.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/O/OliverBuilding.html |title=Oliver Building |publisher=City of Chicago |accessdate=2007-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630144527/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/O/OliverBuilding.html |archivedate=2009-06-30 }}</ref><ref name=\"wolfe\">{{cite book | last = Wolfe | first = Gerard R. | authorlink = Gerard R. Wolfe | title = Chicago: In and Around the Loop | publisher = McGraw-Hill | year = 1996 | location = New York, NY | pages = 53\u201355 | isbn = 0-07-071390-1}}</ref>\n\nThe windows above the second floor are known as \"Chicago windows,\" and are wide window panes bracketed by narrower double-hung windows. The windows also include the name of the company below the central pane.<ref name=\"wolfe\" />\n\nIn the 1990s, when the [[Ford Center for the Performing Arts Oriental Theatre|Oriental Theatre]] wanted to expand its backstage area, architect Daniel P. Coffey came up with a design plan that gutted the Oliver while preserving one-third of its original steel structure, as well as the building's Dearborn facade and a portion of its alley facade.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Kamin | first = Blair | author-link = Blair Kamin | title = The Danger of Becoming Skin Deep | newspaper = Chicago Tribune | date = 2007-04-08 | url = http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/arts/chi-0704060275apr08,1,1281972.story?page=1&coll=chi-ent_arts-hed | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Oliver Building (Chicago)}}\n\n{{Chicago}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Commercial buildings completed in 1908]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Projects by Holabird & Root]]\n[[Category:1908 establishments in Illinois]]\n\n\n{{Chicago-struct-stub}}\n{{Illinois-NRHP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the landmark Chicago building|the Pittsburgh skyscraper|Oliver Building (Pittsburgh)}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n | name =Oliver Building\n | nrhp_type =\n | image =Oliver Typewriter Building Front Door and Design.JPG \n | caption = Oliver Building Front Door with [[Oliver Typewriter Company]] ornamentation\n | designated_other1_name= Chicago Landmark\n | designated_other1_date= May 9, 1984\n | designated_other1_abbr= CL\n | designated_other1_link= Chicago Landmark\n | designated_other1_color= #aaccff\n | location= 159 N. Dearborn, [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States\n | coordinates = {{coord|41|53|05|N|87|37|45.5|W|display=inline,title}}\n| area =\n | built=1907-1908\n | architecture= \n | added = 1984\n | governing_body = Private\n | refnum=83003563 <ref name=\"nris\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/IL/Cook/state7.html|title=ILLINOIS - Cook County |date=2007-07-06|work=National Register of Historic Places|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref>\n}}\n[[File:Oliver Typewriter Company Logo on Building.JPG|thumb|left|upright|[[Oliver Typewriter Company]] ornamentation on Oliver Building (Chicago)]]\n\nThe '''Oliver Building''' is located at 159 N. Dearborn Street in [[Chicago]] within the [[Chicago Loop|Loop]]. It was built for the [[Oliver Typewriter Company]] from 1907-1908 by [[Holabird & Roche]]. When two floors were added in 1920, Holabird & Roche were hired for the expansion. The cast iron exterior features [[typewriter]]-related motifs. It was declared a [[Chicago Landmark]] on May 9, 1984.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/O/OliverBuilding.html |title=Oliver Building |publisher=City of Chicago |accessdate=2007-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630144527/http://www.ci.chi.il.us/Landmarks/O/OliverBuilding.html |archivedate=2009-06-30 }}</ref><ref name=\"wolfe\">{{cite book | last = Wolfe | first = Gerard R. | authorlink = Gerard R. Wolfe | title = Chicago: In and Around the Loop | publisher = McGraw-Hill | year = 1996 | location = New York, NY | pages = 53\u201355 | isbn = 0-07-071390-1}}</ref>\n\nThe windows above the second floor are known as \"Chicago windows,\" and are wide window panes bracketed by narrower double-hung windows. The windows also include the name of the company below the central pane.<ref name=\"wolfe\" />\n\nIn the 1990s, when the [[Ford Center for the Performing Arts Oriental Theatre|Oriental Theatre]] wanted to expand its backstage area, architect Daniel P. Coffey came up with a design plan that gutted the Oliver while preserving one-third of its original steel structure, as well as the building's Dearborn facade and a portion of its alley facade.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Kamin | first = Blair | author-link = Blair Kamin | title = The Danger of Becoming Skin Deep | newspaper = Chicago Tribune | date = 2007-04-08 | url = http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/arts/chi-0704060275apr08,1,1281972.story?page=1&coll=chi-ent_arts-hed | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commonscat|Oliver Building (Chicago)}}\n\n{{Chicago}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Commercial buildings completed in 1908]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Projects by Holabird & Root]]\n[[Category:1908 establishments in Illinois]]\n\n\n{{Chicago-struct-stub}}\n{{Illinois-NRHP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotes:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliver_Building_(Chicago)"}
